  16. (** First-in first-out queues.

  18.    This module implements queues (FIFOs), with in-place modification.
  19.    See {{!examples} the example section} below.
  20. *)

  22. (** {b Unsynchronized accesses} *)

  24. [@@@alert unsynchronized_access
  25.     "Unsynchronized accesses to queues are a programming error."
  26. ]

  28. (**
  29.     Unsynchronized accesses to a queue may lead to an invalid queue state.
  30.     Thus, concurrent accesses to queues must be synchronized (for instance
  31.     with a {!Mutex.t}).
  32. *)

  34. ‌type !'a t
  35. (** The type of queues containing elements of type ['a]. *)


  38. exception Empty
  39. (** Raised when {!Queue.take} or {!Queue.peek} is applied to an empty queue. *)


  42. ‌val create : unit -> 'a t
  43. (** Return a new queue, initially empty. *)

  45. ‌val add : 'a -> 'a t -> unit
  46. (** [add x q] adds the element [x] at the end of the queue [q]. *)

  48. ‌val push : 'a -> 'a t -> unit
  49. (** [push] is a synonym for [add]. *)

  51. ‌val take : 'a t -> 'a
  52. (** [take q] removes and returns the first element in queue [q],
  53.    or raises {!Empty} if the queue is empty. *)

  55. ‌val take_opt : 'a t -> 'a option
  56. (** [take_opt q] removes and returns the first element in queue [q],
  57.    or returns [None] if the queue is empty.
  58.    @since 4.08 *)

  60. ‌val pop : 'a t -> 'a
  61. (** [pop] is a synonym for [take]. *)

  63. ‌val peek : 'a t -> 'a
  64. (** [peek q] returns the first element in queue [q], without removing
  65.    it from the queue, or raises {!Empty} if the queue is empty. *)

  67. ‌val peek_opt : 'a t -> 'a option
  68. (** [peek_opt q] returns the first element in queue [q], without removing
  69.    it from the queue, or returns [None] if the queue is empty.
  70.    @since 4.08 *)

  72. ‌val top : 'a t -> 'a
  73. (** [top] is a synonym for [peek]. *)

  75. ‌val clear : 'a t -> unit
  76. (** Discard all elements from a queue. *)

  78. ‌val copy : 'a t -> 'a t
  79. (** Return a copy of the given queue. *)

  81. ‌val is_empty : 'a t -> bool
  82. (** Return [true] if the given queue is empty, [false] otherwise. *)

  84. ‌val length : 'a t -> int
  85. (** Return the number of elements in a queue. *)

  87. ‌val iter : ('a -> unit) -> 'a t -> unit
  88. (** [iter f q] applies [f] in turn to all elements of [q],
  89.    from the least recently entered to the most recently entered.
  90.    The queue itself is unchanged. *)

  92. ‌val fold : ('acc -> 'a -> 'acc) -> 'acc -> 'a t -> 'acc
  93. (** [fold f accu q] is equivalent to [List.fold_left f accu l],
  94.    where [l] is the list of [q]'s elements. The queue remains
  95.    unchanged. *)

  97. ‌val transfer : 'a t -> 'a t -> unit
  98. (** [transfer q1 q2] adds all of [q1]'s elements at the end of
  99.    the queue [q2], then clears [q1]. It is equivalent to the
  100.    sequence [iter (fun x -> add x q2) q1; clear q1], but runs
  101.    in constant time. *)

  103. (** {1 Iterators} *)

  105. ‌val to_seq : 'a t -> 'a Seq.t
  106. (** Iterate on the queue, in front-to-back order.
  107.     The behavior is not specified if the queue is modified
  108.     during the iteration.
  109.     @since 4.07 *)

  111. ‌val add_seq : 'a t -> 'a Seq.t -> unit
  112. (** Add the elements from a sequence to the end of the queue.
  113.     @since 4.07 *)

  115. ‌val of_seq : 'a Seq.t -> 'a t
  116. (** Create a queue from a sequence.
  117.     @since 4.07 *)

  119. (** {1:examples Examples}

  121.   {2 Basic Example}

  123.    A basic example:
  124.     {[
  125.     # let q = Queue.create ()
  126.     val q : '_weak1 Queue.t = <abstr>


  129.     # Queue.push 1 q; Queue.push 2 q; Queue.push 3 q
  130.     - : unit = ()

  132.     # Queue.length q
  133.     - : int = 3

  135.     # Queue.pop q
  136.     - : int = 1

  138.     # Queue.pop q
  139.     - : int = 2

  141.     # Queue.pop q
  142.     - : int = 3

  144.     # Queue.pop q
  145.     Exception: Stdlib.Queue.Empty.
  146.     ]}

  148.   {2 Search Through a Graph}

  150.    For a more elaborate example, a classic algorithmic use of queues
  151.    is to implement a BFS (breadth-first search) through a graph.

  153.    {[
  154.      type graph = {
  155.        edges: (int, int list) Hashtbl.t
  156.      }

  158.     (* Search in graph [g] using BFS, starting from node [start].
  159.        It returns the first node that satisfies [p], or [None] if
  160.        no node reachable from [start] satisfies [p].
  161.     *)
  162.     let search_for ~(g:graph) ~(start:int) (p:int -> bool) : int option =
  163.       let to_explore = Queue.create() in
  164.       let explored = Hashtbl.create 16 in

  166.       Queue.push start to_explore;
  167.       let rec loop () =
  168.         if Queue.is_empty to_explore then None
  169.         else
  170.           (* node to explore *)
  171.           let node = Queue.pop to_explore in
  172.           explore_node node

  174.       and explore_node node =
  175.         if not (Hashtbl.mem explored node) then (
  176.           if p node then Some node (* found *)
  177.           else (
  178.             Hashtbl.add explored node ();
  179.             let children =
  180.               Hashtbl.find_opt g.edges node
  181.               |> Option.value ~default:[]
  182.             in
  183.             List.iter (fun child -> Queue.push child to_explore) children;
  184.             loop()
  185.           )
  186.         ) else loop()
  187.       in
  188.       loop()

  190.     (* a sample graph *)
  191.     let my_graph: graph =
  192.       let edges =
  193.         List.to_seq [
  194.           1, [2;3];
  195.           2, [10; 11];
  196.           3, [4;5];
  197.           5, [100];
  198.           11, [0; 20];
  199.         ]
  200.         |> Hashtbl.of_seq
  201.       in {edges}

  203.     # search_for ~g:my_graph ~start:1 (fun x -> x = 30)
  204.     - : int option = None

  206.     # search_for ~g:my_graph ~start:1 (fun x -> x >= 15)
  207.     - : int option = Some 20

  209.     # search_for ~g:my_graph ~start:1 (fun x -> x >= 50)
  210.     - : int option = Some 100
  211.    ]}
  212.    *)
